<section>
<h2>Chapter 2 – Probability</h2>

<!-- ================= CONTENT START ================= -->

<div class="card">
<h3>What is Probability?</h3>
<p>
Probability is a branch of mathematics that deals with measuring uncertainty.
It helps us determine how likely an event is to occur under given conditions.
The value of probability always lies between 0 and 1.
A probability of 0 represents an impossible event, whereas a probability of 1
represents a certain event. Probability is widely used in science, engineering,
economics, statistics, and daily life.
</p>
<ul>
<li>0 → Impossible event</li>
<li>1 → Certain event</li>
</ul>
<details>
<summary>Click to see example & formula</summary>
<p>
If the probability of rain tomorrow is 0.7, it means there is a 70% chance of rain.<br><br>
<b>Formula:</b>  
P(E) = Number of favourable outcomes / Total number of outcomes
</p>
</details>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3>Sample Space and Event</h3>
<p>
The sample space is the set of all possible outcomes of a random experiment.
It is denoted by S. An event is any subset of the sample space and represents
one or more outcomes of interest. Understanding sample space is essential for
calculating probability.
</p>
<details>
<summary>Click to see example</summary>
<p>
Tossing a coin:  
S = {H, T}  
Event A (getting head) = {H}
</p>
</details>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3>Equally Likely Events</h3>
<p>
Events are equally likely when each outcome has the same probability of occurring.
This concept applies mainly to fair experiments and is the basis of classical
probability. It makes probability calculations simple and straightforward.
</p>
<details>
<summary>Click to see example</summary>
<p>
In a fair letter dice {A, B, C, D, E, F}, each letter has probability 1/6.
</p>
</details>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3>Complementary Events</h3>
<p>
The complementary event of A consists of all outcomes that do not belong to A.
If event A occurs, its complement cannot occur. The sum of probabilities of an
event and its complement is always equal to 1.
</p>
<details>
<summary>Click to see formula & example</summary>
<p>
<b>Formula:</b> P(A′) = 1 − P(A)<br><br>
If P(A) = 0.4, then P(A′) = 0.6
</p>
</details>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3>Mutually Exclusive Events</h3>
<p>
Two events are mutually exclusive if they cannot occur at the same time.
They have no common outcomes. This concept is important while applying
the addition rule of probability.
</p>
<details>
<summary>Click to see formula & example</summary>
<p>
<b>Formula:</b> P(A ∪ B) = P(A) + P(B)<br><br>
Example: Getting A or F on a letter dice.
</p>
</details>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3>Independent Events</h3>
<p>
Events are independent if the occurrence of one does not affect the probability
of the other. Independent events commonly occur in repeated experiments.
</p>
<details>
<summary>Click to see formula & example</summary>
<p>
<b>Formula:</b> P(A ∩ B) = P(A) × P(B)<br><br>
Example: Tossing two coins.
</p>
</details>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3>Dependent Events</h3>
<p>
Events are dependent when the occurrence of one affects the probability of the other.
This usually happens in sampling without replacement.
</p>
<details>
<summary>Click to see formula & example</summary>
<p>
<b>Formula:</b> P(A ∩ B) = P(A) × P(B|A)<br><br>
Example: Drawing two cards from a deck without replacement.
</p>
</details>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3>Conditional Probability</h3>
<p>
Conditional probability is the probability of an event occurring given that another
event has already occurred. It helps update probabilities using additional information.
</p>
<details>
<summary>Click to see formula & example</summary>
<p>
<b>Formula:</b> P(A|B) = P(A ∩ B) / P(B)<br><br>
Example: Probability of passing an exam given that the student studied.
</p>
</details>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3>Bayes’ Theorem</h3>
<p>
Bayes’ theorem is used to calculate the probability of an event based on prior knowledge.
It plays a vital role in statistics, machine learning, and artificial intelligence.
</p>
<details>
<summary>Click to see formula & example</summary>
<p>
<b>Formula:</b><br>
P(A|B) = [P(B|A) × P(A)] / P(B)<br><br>
Spam filtering based on keywords in emails.
</p>
</details>
</div>

<div class="card">
<h3>What I Learnt in This Chapter</h3>
<ul>
<li>Meaning and importance of probability</li>
<li>Difference between independent and dependent events</li>
<li>Use of conditional probability and Bayes’ theorem</li>
<li>Application of probability in real life</li>
<li>Better decision making using probability</li>
</ul>
</div>

<!-- ================= CONTENT END ================= -->

</section>

<script>
const canvas = document.getElementById("statsBG");
const ctx = canvas.getContext("2d");

function resize(){
  canvas.width = innerWidth;
  canvas.height = innerHeight;
}
resize();
addEventListener("resize", resize);

const points=[];
const COUNT=80;

for(let i=0;i<COUNT;i++){
  points.push({
    x:Math.random()*canvas.width,
    y:Math.random()*canvas.height,
    vx:(Math.random()-0.5)*0.25,
    vy:(Math.random()-0.5)*0.25
  });
}

function animate(){
  ctx.clearRect(0,0,canvas.width,canvas.height);

  for(let i=0;i<COUNT;i++){
    for(let j=i+1;j<COUNT;j++){
      const dx=points[i].x-points[j].x;
      const dy=points[i].y-points[j].y;
      const d=Math.sqrt(dx*dx+dy*dy);
      if(d<120){
        ctx.strokeStyle="rgba(150,170,255,0.12)";
        ctx.beginPath();
        ctx.moveTo(points[i].x,points[i].y);
        ctx.lineTo(points[j].x,points[j].y);
        ctx.stroke();
      }
    }
  }

  points.forEach(p=>{
    p.x+=p.vx; p.y+=p.vy;
    if(p.x<0||p.x>canvas.width) p.vx*=-1;
    if(p.y<0||p.y>canvas.height) p.vy*=-1;
    ctx.fillStyle="rgba(210,220,255,0.6)";
    ctx.beginPath();
    ctx.arc(p.x,p.y,2.2,0,Math.PI*2);
    ctx.fill();
  });

  requestAnimationFrame(animate);
}
animate();
</script>

